snippet.textDisplay:
The Tragic Love Story of Soni and Mahiwal

Long ago, during the reign of the Mughal Empire, there lived a beautiful girl named Soni in Gujarat, a village on the banks of the Chenab River. Her family was well-known for making and selling beautifully decorated pots. Many travelers and traders visited their shop to buy these pots.

One day, an Uzbek merchant named Izzat Baig came to Gujarat for trade. When he saw Soni, he instantly fell in love with her. To see her every day, he started visiting the shop under the pretense of buying pots. Over time, Soni also fell in love with him.

Izzat Baig was so deeply in love that he left his wealthy life behind, gave up his business, and became a simple herder near the Chenab River. The people of Gujarat started calling him ‘Mahiwal,’ which means "the herder." Soni and Mahiwal would secretly meet near the river, longing for a life together. But Soni’s family and the villagers opposed their love. According to their customs, a girl from Gujarat could not marry an outsider.

To keep them apart, Soni’s parents forcefully married her to another man. Heartbroken but determined, Soni continued to meet Mahiwal in secret. Every night, after everyone was asleep, she would take a large baked clay pot and float across the Chenab River to reach him. Their love blossomed despite the odds.

One night, Soni’s sister-in-law discovered her secret. She was furious and wanted to put an end to Soni’s visits. That night, she replaced Soni’s baked clay pot with an unbaked one. When Soni reached the river and placed the pot in the water, it started to dissolve as soon as she tried to float across.

Realizing what was happening, Soni pleaded with the pot to carry her across. She begged, “Please, take me to my beloved Mahiwal. He is waiting for me!” But the pot, being unbaked, could not hold her weight and broke apart in the middle of the river. Soni was helpless as the strong waves pulled her under, and she drowned.

On the other side, Mahiwal anxiously waited for Soni. When he saw her drowning, he jumped into the river to save her, but the river’s currents were too strong. He, too, was swallowed by the water.

Thus, the lovers perished, but their love story became immortal. Even today, the tale of Soni and Mahiwal is remembered as one of the greatest tragedies of true love in history.
